<div class="prose-container centered">
	<p>And taking a step back, it’s a new way to see where we live.</p>
</div>

<div class="intro-image">
</div>

<div class="prose-container">
	<p>When I saw cites from this angle, it was eye-opening.
	</p>
	<p>New York wasn’t just 18 million people—it had a form. Every city was a unique mountain that might be like the steep peaks of lower Manhattan or like the sprawling hills of suburban Atlanta. When I first saw a city in 3D, I had a <i>feel</i> for a city’s size that didn’t exist before.
	</p>
	<p>That feeling goes a long way to improve my own geographic instincts. I know that Kinshasa, DR Congo (13 million) has more people than Paris, France (11 million). But it wasn’t until I saw the population as a form, rather than a number, could I appreciate how large Kinshasa has become in my lifetime.
	</p>
	<p>And this goes for so many nascent metropolises. The world’s population centers are a lot different than 25 years ago. In 1993, there were 14 cities over 10 million people. Today, there are 34, with many of these new megacities sprouting from farmland in our lifetimes.
	</p>
	<p>The shape of these megacities has improved my empathy for the world’s centers of “human” mass, as well as the weight of Asia and Africa on our future. Let’s tour 13 of them.
	</p>
</p>
